<div id="review_3244832660" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3244832660" />
    <a title="Imogen Kathleen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111887831-imogen-kathleen"><img alt="Imogen Kathleen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595965922p2/111887831.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3244832660?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Imogen Kathleen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Imogen Kathleen" href="/user/show/111887831-imogen-kathleen">Imogen Kathleen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780141194073" href="/book/show/9110654-the-beautiful-and-damned">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111887831-imogen-kathleen?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111887831-imogen-kathleen?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3244832660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4354312100986294424"><i>&quot;Here&apos;s to alcohol, the rose colored glasses of life.&quot;</i><br/>Hmmm... I&apos;m torn on the rating for this one. What an ending. <br/>Following the Anthony Patch and Gloria Gilbert, this jazz-age story of decaying glamour is far from my favourite of Fitzgerald&apos;s work, but was nonetheless enchanting.<br/><br/><b>
  <u>The Good</u>
</b><br/><br/>- Fitzgerald&apos;s writing is undeniably beautiful, with a luxurious approach to description that can effortlessly transport the reader to a whole other era.<br/>- As with many of Fitzgerald&apos;s books, there is a heavy</span>
  <span id="freeText4354312100986294424" style="display:none"><i>"Here's to alcohol, the rose colored glasses of life."</i><br />Hmmm... I'm torn on the rating for this one. What an ending. <br />Following the Anthony Patch and Gloria Gilbert, this jazz-age story of decaying glamour is far from my favourite of Fitzgerald's work, but was nonetheless enchanting.<br /><br /><b>
  <u>The Good</u>
</b><br /><br />- Fitzgerald's writing is undeniably beautiful, with a luxurious approach to description that can effortlessly transport the reader to a whole other era.<br />- As with many of Fitzgerald's books, there is a heavy focus on themes of beauty, wealth, and illusion, all of which he is an expert on discussing. <br />- Even where the story lacks, there is immense interest to be found in reading this novel in light of Fitzgerald's own turbulent relationships with fame, alcohol, money, and his wife Zelda. <br />- I know that the ending splits opinion, but I thought that it was perfectly fitted to the themes and ideas running throughout. <br />- Again controversial, I personally love a heavily flawed character, and BOY does Fitzgerald deliver. The beautiful and Damned, with a capital 'D' indeed.<br /><br /><b>
  <u>The Bad</u>
</b> <br /><br />- This book felt like it needed a little... cleaning up? I'm not sure if that makes sense, but I suspect that some of the editing process was rushed in an attempt to follow up on the huge success of 'This Side of Paradise'.<br />- Whilst the characters were fascinating (I am personally not a reader who needs to like a character to be interested in their story), Fitzgerald had yet to reach the depth of character found so easily in 'Gatsby'.<br />- If I was recommending Fitzgerald to someone who had never read him before, I would not start here.<br /><br /><i>At this point, I think that I'll enjoy at least to some extent anything that Fitzgerald wrote. Even his poorer work (of which this is generally held to be the poorest) excites me, though this is perhaps more linked to my interest in the author and his wife than the actual novel would otherwise allow for.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="4354312100986294424" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


